{[show S]The three-card limit raise solves a common problem: you have enough to invite game and a real fit, but only three trumps. A direct jump raise would promise four, so the partnership starts with a forcing 1NT and shows the invitation a step later. Your partner opens 1\S, promising five or more spades and opening values. You have three-card support and invitational strength, the ingredients of a limit raise, just not one you can show directly.
[BID 1N] ⟦Because a direct jump to 3\S would promise four trumps, you begin with a forcing 1NT. Partner must bid again, so the auction stays open and you get a second chance to describe your invitation.⟧ Partner rebids 2\H, naming a second suit as your forcing 1NT requested. Nothing here changes your plan, you already know you want to invite in spades.
[BID 3S] ⟦Now you jump to 3\S. After the forcing 1NT this delayed jump is the three-card limit raise: invitational values with exactly three trumps. A direct 3\S would have shown four, so this two-step route pinpoints your support and hands partner an easy decision.⟧ Partner accepts and raises to 4\S. With the extra values to go past a mere invitation, opener knows the combined hands are worth game opposite three-card support.
[BID Pass] ⟦You pass; 4\S is the final contract.⟧
[show NESW]Well steered. South's \SAT8 \HT6 \DT87 \CAQJT7 is eleven points with only three-card spade support, a limit raise but not the four-trump kind. The forcing 1NT and the jump to 3\S told exactly that story, and opener, holding values to spare, carried on to game. Three trumps and an invitation: show it in two steps and let opener place the contract.}
[Note "1:forcing 1NT"]
