{[show S]When you hold three-card support for partner's major and just enough to invite, you can't raise straight to three, that jump promises four trumps. The forcing 1NT lets you show the invitation while still telling partner the support is only three. Your partner opens 1\S, showing five or more spades and opening values. You have a spade fit and invitational values, but with only three trumps a direct raise to 3\S would overstate the fit.
[BID 1N] ⟦So you bid a forcing 1NT first. It says nothing about spades yet; it simply forces partner to bid again and buys you the room to reveal a three-card limit raise on the next round.⟧ Partner rebids 2\D, showing a second suit. That is exactly the extra shape your forcing 1NT asked for, and it clears the way for your real message.
[BID 3S] ⟦Now you jump to 3\S. Delayed like this, after the forcing 1NT rather than in direct answer to the opening, it promises invitational strength with only three trumps, not the four a direct 3\S would show. Partner can now judge game precisely.⟧ Partner accepts, bidding 4\S. Holding more than a bare minimum, opener adds it to your invitation and three-card support and knows game is the right spot.
[BID Pass] ⟦You pass; 4\S is the final contract.⟧
[show NESW]Nicely handled. South's \ST93 \HAJ7 \DQJ9 \CQJ64 is eleven balanced points with three-card spade support, a limit raise minus the fourth trump. The forcing 1NT then the jump to 3\S showed precisely that, and opener, with the values to accept, pushed on to 4\S. Two steps beat one loud jump when your support is only three cards.}
